Parliament does not support the amendment granting freedom to Tymoshenko
Today, the Parliament of Ukraine, in its amendment to the Code of Criminal Procedure, rejected an attempt to repeal an article that condemned the leader of the opposition, Julia Timoshenko.
An amendment that would result in the release of the former Prime Minister in prison was rejected during the second reading of the draft law on commutation of sentences for economic offences.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for signing a gas deal with Russia, which was found to be unprofitable.
The sentence is not yet final; the court will consider the appeal of Tymoshenko in December.
Timoshenko claims that the sentence is the political revenge of the regime; in the West, the trial was also suspected of bias.
The proposal to repeal Article 365 of the Code of Criminal Procedure, according to which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was supported by 147 members of Parliament.
It would require 226 votes for ratification.
