Trends in travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, only five government tourist agencies were able to operate in the former Czechoslovakia: Çedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Since travel to the West was severely restricted, tourism agencies of the time mostly sold to countries of the socialist bloc.
Thus, on vacation, Czech tourists traveled to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea on the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both countries on the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balaton).
The only exception was from 1962 to 1972, when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia, and then the Yugoslav regime returned to the West, with significant restrictions on the travel of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia.
A major paradox of the socialist period was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. and Czechoslovakia) were not allowed individual visits on socialist countries.
If a Czechoslovakian national wanted to travel by himself, for example, to the Soviet Union or Poland, a letter of invitation was necessary from that country; otherwise an individual journey was impossible.
At the time, travel agencies were offering trips to the West, but you had to either take turns all night, have a sleeping bag, or have nice friends in the agency.
And that was not all.
The money was needed to travel to the West and was not issued to politically unreliable people who were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czech currency was not freely convertible; without a currency permit, it was impossible to obtain money (Western currency) to travel to the West.
The most common practice for the Czechs was their home leave, which has resulted in large numbers of cottages and summer homes, and this continues to be the custom.
Since 1989, tourism in the Czech Republic has thus undergone a real revolution.
While before 1989 GDR or Bulgaria was the culmination of our journeys, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million vacations worldwide.
The great paradox that we no longer realize is that until 1989 we were not free to visit Croatia's most popular now, since it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
At the beginning of 1990, the need to obtain visas for neighbouring Western European countries was abolished, beginning a huge wave of short journeys, mainly to Vienna and Germany.
Everyone wanted to go there for a moment.
In Paris, for example, Czech tourists slept in parks in tents because their income at the time was not enough for a hotel or a boarding house.
A typical feature of Czech tourism at that time was the desire to bring in its own food (cans, salami, etc.) to save money.
Another important point is the introduction of a freely convertible Czech kroner, and after a decade, our tourists can finally buy the Western currency freely.
Our standard of living and average income grew, leading to another important circumstance around 1997.
Since 1997, increased demand has made it possible for travel agencies to prepare regular flights by chartered airlines, which, compared to the past, have now become incredibly cheap because of the ability to order flat discounts.
By the late 1990s, Czechs did not need a visa to visit virtually all the developed world countries except the United States, which made our journeys even easier.
The following significant event in the post-revolution period occurred in 2000, with great demand leading to the historic first direct charter flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country, Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights have taken Czech tourists to warm exotic countries, and these winter flights from the Czech Republic will be sent along twelve exotic tracks.
Currently, some 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another major event of this period, symbolizing our development after the revolution, took place in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the United States lifted the need to obtain a visa for Czech tourists, and my country has thus forever joined the world's most developed countries.
For the first time in 2008 Czechs spent more than half of their vacations abroad (50.3 per cent); for the first time in history, they spent more than 15,000 crowns per person during leave abroad, including their expenses at their destination.
