7 lessons from a lost interview by Steve Jobs that show at the theater this week
After the death of Steve Jobs on 5 October, some compared him to Henry Ford, describing the technical genius as the Great Instigator of Today.
But the fact that Apple fans can count as the biggest discovery in the newly discovered interview, which was remembered in advance of the pre-screening in major markets this week, is how much this creative mind has understood in business processes and manufacturing technologies.
He was, of course, a designer, a dreamer, and considered himself a hippy, but he was also a perfect organizer and modernist of the production process, who believed that many business leaders suffered from “the disease of thinking that a really big idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] a big idea from a big product separates a huge amount of artificial labour”
Back in 1995, Bob Kringley created a TV series called Triumph Nerds on the advent of his personal computer, and he spent more than an hour with Jobs in a unique long conversation.
By that time, it had been about 10 years since Jobs was expelled from Apple, and he was already working at his new NeXT computer company in anticipation of the massive development of the Internet.
While a small part of Kringley's interview was used in Nerdas, he says the originals were missing in transportation.
Only after Jobs' death did a complete VHS copy be found in the director's garage.
This piece of material, slightly edited, was the basis for Steve Jobs' 68-minute film: A Lost Interview, which goes to Landmark Theatres on this Wednesday and Thursday.
For a man who's known for his hatred of a detailed interview, Jobs seems to be not used to setting out his technological philosophy and business strategy.
And incredibly thoughtful.
In four different points in the interview, there are big intervals between questions and answers -- reflections for 10-15 seconds, where Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts to tell more.
There are also moments where Jobs' perfectionism goes to the surface, where he seems angry with Kringley's issues, making him move faster to issues or to events of greater importance.
In the lost interview in Pixar, Aypods, and Aiphones that he had dropped before, there was something evil prophetic when Jobs was evaluating what he saw different companies doing right and wrong and offering their own vision of future information technology.
One thing to read about the fatal assessments of Jobs' work, but there's something that's wounding and inspiring in Jobs that we see here, an alarming dreamer on the threshold of greatness.
He has a vision of what things could and should be.
Shortly after he told everyone here, he went and did it.
A small summary of the seven significant findings of the lost interview:
How he learned how to run a business:
I kept asking: \"Why do you do this\" and the answers you always get: \"Oh, it just does that.\"
Nobody knows why they do what they do, nobody thinks very deep in the business.
That's what I found out.
Jobs continue to describe in detail their attempts to rationalize reporting in Apple.
