UNAM Asphalt can avoid cracks
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the UNAM School of Chemistry, developed a polymer-modified bitum to produce a mixture of best quality that is resistant to environmental and temperature effects.
If road-covered signals were to be given attention, it would be necessary to repair about 200,000 pits per rainy season in a capital area in the Valley of Mexico City, says Rafael Herrera Naher, a UNAM professor of chemistry, and adds that if the process of construction and maintenance of asphalt road surface is correct, the number of pits can be reduced or even reduced to zero.
His lecture on pits, read during the International Year of Chemistry, reports that the laboratory for which he is responsible develops a polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture of near-bitum characteristics, but with better resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Naher said that this type of modified bitumen could be used in areas where the weather was extremely hot, as in some towns in the north, to improve road quality and hence to resist the formation of pits.
He explained that bitumen, the hardest part of oil, was a sequence of hydrocarbon molecules, one a high molecular mass called asphaltenes, and the others a low molecular mass called Maltens, which together gave the road cover to its characteristic viscous behaviour.
The viscous behaviour of a bitumen is the fact that it behaves like a liquid at 120 degrees on high temperatures, and at 50 degrees Celsius it remains almost solid, while at very low temperatures the bitumen becomes fragile, he said.
This means that the resistance of the street asphalt is not constant, but changes during the day, depending on natural conditions and temperature, the chemical engineering specialist said.
He observed that Mexico City streets were mainly covered with flexible coatings, consisting of six layers of material, of which the latter three include bitumen.
Among the top layers is a bitumen made of small stones thrown into and then sprayed with bitumen.
Every stone that makes it up, he said, is loaded into a bitumen.
In driving and exerting effort, this helps forces to be very well distributed along the road.
If it were a modified asphalt, they would be even better distributed, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphalt covering, he added, the last layer, called the wear layer, which is made of small rock, is actually sand that is also loaded into asphalt.
Since it is a layer that will communicate with the wheels of transport, it must have more resistance than asphalt covering and road friction.
As part of the road surface that will receive and disseminate these efforts, the wear layer also requires proper thickness and the material from which it is made must be taken into account.
The weather, especially humidity and temperature changes, were also very important factors for consideration, especially water, because it had a significant impact on the condition of asphalt.
When the ground is raw, the water penetrates the surface and it is difficult to get out of it, causing all layers of the surface to soften and thus producing pits.
When producing pits, he said, the first person will find a layer of wear and only then will it affect the bitumen, but the damage does not happen instantly, a process that should be taken into account at the first signs of the current repair programmes.
A member of the National Research System also explained that transport loads were another important factor in the formation of holes, and therefore the thickness of each surface area must always be related to the transport load and this requirement must be met to prevent frequent pits.
Rafael Herrera said that there was still much to be learned and done about bitumen, for example, that in other countries were already on the market and even helped to make pits light and without using high temperatures.
